L lateral eyebrow/temporal area:  The wound was irrigated w/ copious amounts of sterile water and the surrounding skin was cleaned with betadine.  3 cc of 1% plain lidocaine were then injected superficially and anesthesia was achieved.  The wound was then explored to look for any foreign body.  No foreign body was found.  Upon talking w/ the patient and explaining to him that there is still a possibility of a foreign body, we agreed on proceeding w/ wound closure in order to avoid significant scaring due to the wound closing by secondary intention.  The wound was then approximated using 7, 6-0 nylon, simple interrupted stitches.  < 1 cc of bleeding resulted. The patient tolerated the procedure well.  We will proceed to get a skull series to r/o foreign body.  The patient was also contacted to come back to get a tetanus shot.  If not done today, he will receive it on 07/12/10. The patient was placed in the prone position, local anesthesia was achieved using 6mL of 1 percent plain lidocaine and the skin was prepped with betadine solution and draped in sterile fashion. Copious amounts of sterile saline solution were used to irrigate the wound prior to approximation of the wound edges.  5,  3-O Nylon horizontal mattress sutures were placed in the dermis.  A running baseball suture w/ a total of 5 sutures was placed to better approximate wound edges.  Bacitracin ointment and a sterile dressing were then applied.  Wound care instructions were given to the patient. The specimen was sent to pathology in normal saline solution.  Final specimen length approximately 1.5cm. The patient tolerated the procedure well and there was approximately 3mL of blood loss.
